---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import LessonNav from "../../components/LessonNav.astro";
import SeeAlso from "../../components/SeeAlso.astro";
import InstallPicker from "../../components/InstallPicker";
import HeroMesh from "../../components/HeroMesh";

const TEST_PEER_NPUB = "npub1qmc3cvfz0yu2hx96nq3gp55zdan2qclealn7xshgr448d3nh6lks7zel98";
const TEST_PEER_ADDR = "217.77.8.91:2121";
---

<Base title="Try It">
  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <p class="text-fips-accent font-mono text-sm mb-2">Lesson 13</p>
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-8">Try It</h1>

    <section class="space-y-4 text-fips-text leading-relaxed">
      <p>
        Twelve lessons of diagrams and byte layouts are enough. The rest of the protocol makes a lot
        more sense once you watch a real node boot, run a handshake, and show up in a spanning tree
        you can poke at. This page has everything you need to get there.
      </p>

      <p>The plan:</p>

      <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-1 text-fips-muted text-sm">
        <li>Build or install the <code class="font-mono">fips</code> daemon.</li>
        <li>
          Point it at the public test node. The Debian and macOS packages ship this peer in the
          default config, so most of you can skip the config step.
        </li>
        <li>Start the service and confirm you joined the mesh.</li>
        <li>
          Send a packet across it. Ping a peer by <code class="font-mono">.fips</code> name or SSH into
          a mesh-reachable host.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">The public test node</h2>

      <div
        class="rounded-lg border border-fips-border bg-fips-surface/30 p-4 font-mono text-xs space-y-1 text-fips-muted"
      >
        <div>
          <span class="text-fips-accent">alias </span>fips-test-node
        </div>
        <div>
          <span class="text-fips-accent">npub </span><span class="text-fips-text break-all"
            >{TEST_PEER_NPUB}</span
          >
        </div>
        <div>
          <span class="text-fips-accent">udp </span><span class="text-fips-text"
            >{TEST_PEER_ADDR}</span
          >
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        It is a plain FIPS node with <code class="font-mono">auto_connect</code> open to inbound UDP.
        When your node starts, it runs a Noise IK handshake with the test node, builds a link, and joins
        whatever tree the test node is part of. No other configuration is required.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Prerequisites</h2>

      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1 text-fips-muted text-sm">
        <li>Rust 1.85 or newer (edition 2024). The project pins the toolchain in its lockfile.</li>
        <li>
          Admin privileges on the host. The daemon creates a TUN device (<code class="font-mono"
            >fips0</code
          > on Linux, <code class="font-mono">utunN</code> on macOS), which the kernel will not give you
          as an unprivileged user.
        </li>
        <li>
          Outbound UDP on port 2121. If the test-node handshake never completes, a firewall or CGNAT
          is the first thing to check.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Install and connect</h2>

      <p>
        Pick a platform. Every code block has a copy button. The commands come straight from the
        <a
          href="https://github.com/jmcorgan/fips#installation"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener"
          class="text-fips-accent underline">project README</a
        >, so when the upstream install changes, this page is the first thing we update.
      </p>

      <InstallPicker client:visible />

      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Your first packet</h2>

      <p>
        Once <code class="font-mono">fipsctl show peers</code> lists the test node with state
        <code class="font-mono">Authenticated</code> and the spanning tree has at least two nodes in it,
        the mesh is usable. Try any of these:
      </p>

      <div class="space-y-3">
        <div>
          <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-fips-muted mb-1">
            Reach the test node by name
          </div>
          <pre
            class="rounded border border-fips-border bg-fips-bg p-3 text-xs font-mono text-fips-text overflow-x-auto whitespace-pre">{`ping6 ${TEST_PEER_NPUB}.fips`}</pre>
          <p class="text-xs text-fips-muted mt-1">
            On macOS use <code class="font-mono">ping6</code>, not
            <code class="font-mono">ping</code>. macOS ships them as two separate binaries and the
            IPv4 one will not resolve AAAA records.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-fips-muted mb-1">
            Watch the mesh in real time
          </div>
          <pre
            class="rounded border border-fips-border bg-fips-bg p-3 text-xs font-mono text-fips-text overflow-x-auto whitespace-pre">{`fipstop`}</pre>
          <p class="text-xs text-fips-muted mt-1">
            A TUI dashboard for status, peers, links, sessions, tree, transports, and routing. Press
            <code class="font-mono">q</code> to quit.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-fips-muted mb-1">
            Run something over it
          </div>
          <pre
            class="rounded border border-fips-border bg-fips-bg p-3 text-xs font-mono text-fips-text overflow-x-auto whitespace-pre">{`ssh -6 npub1...xxx.fips
curl -6 http://npub1...yyy.fips/`}</pre>
          <p class="text-xs text-fips-muted mt-1">
            Anything that takes an IPv6 address works. The flag forces the tool to use IPv6 and pick
            up the <code class="font-mono">AAAA</code> record from the FIPS resolver.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">When it does not work</h2>

      <div class="space-y-3">
        <div class="rounded border border-fips-border p-3">
          <p class="font-semibold text-sm text-fips-text mb-1">Handshake never completes</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-fips-muted">
            Outbound UDP 2121 is blocked, you are behind a symmetric NAT, or IPv4 connectivity to
            <code class="font-mono">{TEST_PEER_ADDR}</code> is dropped. Try a different network or add
            a TCP fallback under <code class="font-mono">transports.tcp</code>.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded border border-fips-border p-3">
          <p class="font-semibold text-sm text-fips-text mb-1">
            <code class="font-mono">.fips</code> names do not resolve
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm text-fips-muted">
            On tarball installs you have to point your system resolver at
            <code class="font-mono">127.0.0.1:5354</code> for the <code class="font-mono">fips</code
            >
            domain. The Debian and macOS packages do this for you. Check with
            <code class="font-mono">dig @127.0.0.1 -p 5354 npub1...xxx.fips AAAA</code>.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded border border-fips-border p-3">
          <p class="font-semibold text-sm text-fips-text mb-1">
            Tree stays at one node (just yourself)
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm text-fips-muted">
            The link is up but no spanning-tree announcements have arrived yet. Give it a few
            seconds. If it persists, <code class="font-mono">fipsctl show links</code> will tell you whether
            the link is authenticated and which metrics MMP has collected so far.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Where to go from here</h2>

      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-fips-muted text-sm">
        <li>
          Add a persistent identity. Set <code class="font-mono"
            >node.identity.persistent: true</code
          >
          in your config so your npub survives restarts and your peers can pin it.
        </li>
        <li>
          Bring a service online. The
          <a
            href="https://github.com/jmcorgan/fips/tree/master/examples/sidecar-nostr-relay"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener"
            class="text-fips-accent underline">strfry sidecar example</a
          > runs a Nostr relay that is only reachable through the mesh. About twenty lines of docker-compose.
        </li>
        <li>
          Expose a second device. Run <code class="font-mono">fips-gateway</code> on a home server and
          reach mesh peers from a laptop that does not have FIPS installed. Lesson 12 covers how the NAT
          plumbing works.
        </li>
        <li>
          Read the specs that generated this site:
          <a
            href="https://github.com/jmcorgan/fips/tree/master/docs/design"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener"
            class="text-fips-accent underline">docs/design</a
          >. Everything in these lessons is grounded in those documents.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p class="mt-6 text-fips-muted text-sm">
        Break something useful, open an issue, or put up a second test node. The mesh gets more
        interesting with every peer that joins it.
      </p>
    </section>

    <SeeAlso terms={["fips", "node_addr", "fips-gateway", "ipv6-ula", "identity-cache"]} />
    <LessonNav current={13} />
  </article>

  <section class="hex-bg relative overflow-hidden">
    <div class="hero-mesh-wrap absolute inset-0">
      <HeroMesh client:load />
      <div class="hero-mesh-fade absolute inset-0 pointer-events-none"></div>
    </div>
    <figure class="relative max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 pt-16 pb-40 md:pb-48">
      <span
        aria-hidden="true"
        class="absolute -top-2 left-4 md:left-6 text-fips-accent font-mono text-6xl leading-none select-none"
        >&ldquo;</span
      >
      <blockquote class="text-fips-text text-lg md:text-xl leading-relaxed italic">
        <p class="mb-4">
          Engineering solutions to problems is mostly about assembling existing pieces into a new
          whole, more so than inventing a new wheel.
        </p>
        <p>
          FIPS combines known, battle tested concepts going back decades in the fields of
          networking, cryptography, distributed computing, resilient communications, and operating
          systems, with full credit to those who came before.
        </p>
      </blockquote>
      <figcaption class="mt-6 text-sm text-fips-muted font-mono">
        &mdash;
        <a
          href="https://njump.to/nevent1qqsqjkq3yxynqsj7lkk6dst9h4el8yx4rlwysn8pngqewpxk9aqttncpzamhxue69uhhyetvv9ujumn0wvh8xmmrd9skctczyq4m4nj48mlt7kxa2kgjz60e9sgj86mpy8tm5zf0d3gpqjhuxxkw7qcyqqqqqqgg0hv3z"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener"
          class="text-fips-accent hover:underline">Johnathan Corgan</a
        >, author of FIPS
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>
</Base>
